				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Cash-Stuffed German Companies on a Global Buying Spree</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By David Gelles			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-09-22T16:18:58+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">September 22, 2014 12:18 pm</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">September 22, 2014 12:18 pm</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content">
	<div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/09/23/business/LIFE/LIFE-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/09/23/business/LIFE/LIFE-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/09/23/business/LIFE/LIFE-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000003131566" width="592" height="395" alt="A laboratory technician inspecting tablets at Merck. Merck of Germany is buying Sigma-Aldrich."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="395"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">A laboratory technician inspecting tablets at Merck. Merck of Germany is buying Sigma-Aldrich.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Krisztian Bocsi/Bloomberg News, via Getty Images</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/09/22/german-companies-continue-their-buying-spree/" data-title="Cash-Stuffed German Companies on a Global Buying Spree" data-description="A rare bright spot in the European economy in recent years, many of the biggest German companies have begun capitalizing on their strength, striking big deals for overseas competitors.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Germanyâs businesses have been the rare bright spot in the European economy in recent years, generating jobs and profits even as neighboring countries face persistent unemployment.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Now, many of the biggest German companies are capitalizing on their strength and striking big deals for overseas competitors.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In recent days, two multibillion-dollar deals were announced. On Sunday, the German engineering conglomerate <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=SI&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Siemens A.G">Siemens</a> announced a $7.6 billion acquisition of the <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=DRC&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Dresser-Rand Group Inc">Dresser-Rand Group</a>, the United States oil products company. And on Monday morning, Merck of Germany, the chemical and drug giant, said it would pay $17 billion for <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=SIAL&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Sigma-Aldrich Corporation">Sigma-Aldrich</a>, an American life sciences company. (The German <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=MRK&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Merck &#038; Company Inc">Merck</a> is not affiliated with the United States drug maker Merck &#038; Company.)</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThe overall confidence that is still prevalent here is a big factor,â said Tim Brandi, head of corporate practice at the law firm Hogan Lovells in Frankfurt. âItâs been a big rush in just a weekâs time.â</p>
<div class="w480"><figure class="promo media video blog-video "
    data-videoid="100000003131076" data-media-action="modal" data-autoplay="" data-embedded="true" aria-label="media" role="group">
        <span class="visually-hidden">Video</span>

    <figcaption class="caption">
        <h4 class="headline">Germanyâs Merck to Acquire Sigma-Aldrich</h4>
		        <div class="caption-video">
                <div class="summary-credit">
            <p class="summary">Karl Ludwig-Kley, chairman of Merck of Germany, and Rakesh Sachdev, chief of Sigma-Aldrich, explain deal $17 billion deal for the life sciences company.</p>
            <span class="credit video-credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder">
                                                                    <span class="visually-hidden">Publish Date </span>September 22, 2014.
                            </span>
            <span class="credit photo-credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder">
                            </span>
        </div>

                    <div class="sharetools-video-container">
                <div id="sharetools-video-tools-100000003131076"
